04482nam a22007095i 9780231546140DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20182017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017015324  a97802315461407 a10.7312/baty185402doi  a(DE-B1597)493817  a(OCoLC)1046606455  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPG3321.B4bA2 2018 4aPG3321.B4bA2 2018 7aLCO0140002bisacsh1 aBatyushkov, Konstantin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWritings from the Golden Age of Russian Poetry /cKonstantin Batyushkov. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRussian Library00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. VOLOGDA TO ST. PETERSBURG -- t2. WAR AND PEACE -- t3. THE CITY AND THE COUNTRY -- t4. BACK TO WAR -- t5. THE RETURN OF ODYSSEUS -- t6. ARZAMAS AND THE ESSAYS -- t7. TO ITALY -- t8. INTO THE DARK -- tNOTES -- tTRANSLATOR’S NOTE -- tINDEX OF TEXTS BY BATYUSHKOV CITED OR DISCUSSED 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKonstantin Batyushkov was one of the great poets of the Golden Age of Russian literature in the early nineteenth century. His verses, famous for their musicality, earned him the admiration of Alexander Pushkin and generations of Russian poets to come. In Writings from the Golden Age of Russian Poetry, Peter France interweaves Batyushkov’s life and writings, presenting masterful new translations of his work with the compelling story of Batyushkov’s career as a soldier, diplomat, and poet and his tragic decline into mental illness at the age of thirty-four. Little known among non-Russian readers, Batyushkov left a varied body of writing, both in verse and in prose, as well as memorable letters to friends. France nests a substantial selection of his sprightly epistles on love, friendship, and social life, his often tragic elegies, and extracts from his essays and letters within episodes of his remarkable life—particularly appropriate for a poet whose motto was “write as you live, and live as you write.” Batyushkov’s writing reflects the transition from the urbane sociability of the Enlightenment to the rebellious sensibility of Pushkin and Lermontov; it spans the Napoleonic Wars and the rapid social and literary change from Catherine the Great to Nicholas I. Presenting Batyushkov’s poetry of feeling and wit alongside his troubled life, Writings from the Golden Age of Russian Poetry makes his verse accessible to English-speaking readers in a necessary exploration of this transitional moment for Russian literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aPoets, Russiany19th centuryvBiography. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aFrance, Peter08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2017z978311065472108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/baty1854040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231546140423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231546140.jpg  a978-3-11-054330-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  a978-3-11-065472-1  CUP eBook Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK